773. Disabil Rehabil. 2002 May 10;24(7):378-82. doi: 10.1080/09638280110096269.

Disability Adjusted Life Years (DALYs) and rehabilitation.

Jelsma J(1), De Weerdt W, De Cock P.

Author information:
(1)Division of Physiotherapy, School of Health and Rehabilitation Sciences, 
University of Cape Town, South Africa. jjelsma@uctgshl.uct.ac.za

PURPOSE: The Disability Adjusted Life Year (DALY) is a unit that was developed 
for use in cost-effectiveness analysis and epidemiology studies. It is a 
combined measure of both death and disability, and has been extensively utilized 
in several countries and across various conditions. The purpose of this paper is 
to examine the implications for rehabilitation of the widespread use of this 
measure.
METHOD: The premises upon which the disability weight were developed are 
examined in the light of existing literature.
CONCLUSION: It is concluded that, whereas the incorporation of the impact of 
disability on disease burden is to be lauded, the DALY is insensitive to changes 
in disability status. Consequently, resource allocation to rehabilitation 
activities based on cost-effectiveness analysis using DALYs may be diminished. 
There is also a dearth of epidemiological information relating to disability and 
it is incumbent on rehabilitation professionals to address this lack. The DALY 
protocol is under revision and those concerned with rehabilitation issues should 
contribute to the debates surrounding cost-effectiveness analysis and the units 
that are used to determine the effectiveness component.

