Despite the fact that life expectancy at birth in Mexico has improved from 
forty-two years in 1940 to seventy-three in 2000, major inequalities persist in 
health and access to health care. The Mexican health care system has evolved 
into a series of disjointed subsystems that are incapable of delivering 
